    "summary": "Background: Alzheimer's disease (AD) is characterised by progressive memory loss, with synaptic dysfunction emerging as a key early event. While deficits in synaptic mitochondrial bioenergetics have been proposed to be involved in AD pathophysiology, the precise underlying biochemical mechanisms remain largely unknown. Methods: This study employed a range of biochemical approaches, including quantitative mass spectrometry-based proteomics, western blotting, and enzymatic activity analyses. It investigated synaptic-enriched fractions from the forebrain of 3-4 month-old wild-type (WT) mice and amyloid precursor protein transgenic (APPtg) mice, a model of AD-related amyloid deposition. Tissue from two behavioural groups of mice was analysed, one group under basal conditions (with no behaviour"
